August 1, 2016

Word Clouds

Created some word clouds for one-star and five-star businesses to see if there’s a difference between the words reviewers use for each rating using wordcloud library. Expect to see a relationship between negative words and one-star ratings and positive words and five-star ratings.

reviews_text <- read_csv("../clean_data/reviews_text.csv")
one <- reviews_text %>% 
  filter(stars == 1) %>% 
  group_by(word) %>% 
  count() %>% 
  top_n(100) %>% 
  arrange(n)
## Selecting by n
five <- reviews_text %>% 
  filter(stars == 5) %>% 
  group_by(word) %>% 
  count() %>% 
  top_n(100) %>% 
  arrange(n)
## Selecting by n
col <- c("salmon1", "tomato2", "orangered3", "red3", "firebrick4")
wordcloud(one$word, one$n, scale = c(4, 0.25),
          random.order = F, random.color = F,
          use.r.layout = T, rot.per = .35,
          colors = col)

green <- c("chartreuse2", "mediumseagreen", "forestgreen", 
           "seagreen", "darkgreen")
wordcloud(five$word, five$n, scale = c(4, 0.25),
          random.order = F, random.color = F,
          use.r.layout = T, rot.per = .35,
          colors = green)

The main words are similar for both clouds like “food” and “service”, probably because it was bad food and service for one-star restaurants and great food and service for five-star restaurants. Evidence of this is present in the other words like “love”, “friendly”, “excellent”, “happy” for five-stars and “bad”, “rude”, “worst”, “wait”, “horrible” for one-stars.
